A: The problem is that you are trying to create a PrintWriter with a filename, not a File object. The correct way is to pass a File object to the PrintWriter constructor.
Here is the corrected code:
import java.io.PrintWriter;
import java.io.File;

public class Testing {
  public static void main(String[] args) {
    File file = new File("C:/Users/Me/Desktop/directory/file.txt");
    PrintWriter printWriter = new PrintWriter(file);
    printWriter.println("hello");
    printWriter.close();
  }
}

This code will create a new file at the specified location if it doesn't exist, and then write "hello" to the file. If the file already exists, it will overwrite the existing content.

